results.raw: Hennepin, Ramsey, and Anoka Counties Under Curfew Beginning at 7 P.M. at Minneapolis-St Paul Int'l Airport
results.title: Hennepin, Ramsey, and Anoka Counties Under Curfew Beginning at 7 P.M.

-MY6_ZDcfpvH0HaXafA1.text: Incident reported at Minneapolis-St Paul Int'l Airport.

-MY6_ZKSBV2OGuEEdtxg.text: Governor Walz announced that Hennepin, Ramsey, and Anoka counties will be under a curfew from 7 p.m. tonight until 6 a.m. tomorrow.

nib.text:
In a Monday afternoon press conference, Minnesota officials announced that Hennepin, Ramsey, and Anoka counties will all be under curfew from 7 p.m. Monday night until 6 a.m. Tuesday morning.

Officials advised that there would be exemptions for credentialed press, law enforcement, emergency responders, those traveling to and from work, and community patrols.

Minneapolis Mayor Jacob Frey noted that the curfews are in response to the police shooting of Daunte Wright in Brooklyn Center. “This anguish that we’re all suffering cannot translate into violence … We must see peace tonight,” Mayor Frey said in the Monday afternoon briefing.

Major General Shawn Manke of the MN National Guard added that Guard deployments would expand from 500 personnel as of Monday morning to over 1,000 by the end of the day on Tuesday in order to support Phase 3 of Operation Safety Net. He said they would be deployed throughout Minneapolis, St. Paul, and Brooklyn Center.

Additional personnel will be placed in staging areas until they are assigned specific missions and shift rotations based on needs and conditions on the ground.

Manke dispelled rumors that the guard has used nonlethal munitions in and around Minneapolis-St Paul.

“We are committed to meeting the intent of Operation Safety Net, to protect the communities and the people while preserving their constitutional rights and the peaceful expression of First Amendment Rights,” he said.
